Load data

Load already pre-processed data (see pre-processing-AIT.R for details).

# Load dataset
data <- read_csv('AIT_longformat.csv', col_names=TRUE)

# Select some columns and change their names
df <- data %>% 
  transmute(
    id = participant,
    trialN = trials.thisN,
    emo5 = Emotion,
    emo3 = Emotion3,
    fb = feedback,
    bpm_pre = BPM_Pre,
    bpm_post = BPM_Post,
    psc = (BPM_Post-BPM_Pre)/BPM_Pre * 100,
    arousal = arousal.response, 
    valence = valenc.response,
    iacc = IAcc,
    iacc_bin = IAccBin
    )

Exclusions

  • Participants with no Interoceptive Accuracy data (missed recording values)
  • 1 participant missing value
  • Participants with extreme PSC values
# NA in IACC column
excluded_iacc <- c(8,17,29,40,42,45,50,52,53)
# mysterious NA in id
# 23 bad, 15 good, 11 NA
excluded_psc <- c(5,23,35,36,37,38,39,40,51)
#excluded_psc <- c(3,9,23,30,35,36,37,38,49,51,54,57)
#excluded_psc <- c(3,9,23,35,36,37,51,57)

df <- df %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  filter(!(id %in% excluded_iacc)) %>%
  filter(!(id %in% excluded_psc)) %>%
  filter(psc > -15 & psc < 15) # filter unwanted values (PSC)

Hypotheses and analysis plan

Hypotheses

  1. Manipulation check of arousal induction
  1. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence arousal ratings : Within-subject ANOVA (arousal ~ category)
  2. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence valence ratings : Within-subject ANOVA (valence ~ category)
  3. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence HR deceleration : Within-subject ANOVA (hr ~ category)
  1. HR is correlated with arousal ratings : Pearson’s correlation (hr x arousal)
  2. HR is not correlated with valence ratings : Pearson’s correlation (hr x valence)
  3. Interoceptive Accuracy (IAcc) is not correlated with arousal ratings : Pearson’s correlation (IAcc x arousal)
  4. Interoceptive Accuracy (IAcc) is not correlated with valence ratings : Pearson’s correlation (IAcc x valence)
  1. Cardiac feedback
  1. Feedback effect on arousal ratings (interaction with IAcc) : Mixed MR ANOVA model (arousal ~ category + feedback * IAcc )
  2. No feedback effect on valence ratings : Mixed MR ANOVA model (valence ~ category + feedback * IAcc )

Alternative:

  1. Linear Mixed Model (arousal ~ category + feedback * IAcc + (1|id))
  2. Linear Mixed Model (valence ~ category + feedback * IAcc + (1|id))

Does the image category affect arousal, valence ratings and heart rate deceleration?

Heart rate deceleration

Do the images affect heart rate?

“Dunn 2010: Overall, participants showed an HR deceleration when viewing the images, a finding consistent with an initial orienting response (e.g., Bradley, 2000). HR deceleration was greater for negative images than for positive and neutral images, F(2, 51) = 3.29, p < .05 (cf. Dunn et al., 2009).”

df %>%
  group_by(emo3) %>%
  summarize(hr_mean = mean(psc),
            hr_sd = sd(psc))

=> Data shows HR deceleration to images (in the means).

Let’s check with Within-Subjects ANOVA:

df %>%

Assumptions check

  1. Errors (a.k.a. residuals) are normally distributed (qqnorm and hist)
  2. Variances are homogeneous (heteroscedasticity) : Verified using Levene’s Test for Homogeneity of Variances
  3. Model effects are additive · Verified using the Tukey 1-df Test for Nonadditivity
  4. Errors are independent

Assumptions check for linear mixed model

  1. Linearity and homoskedasticity
  • Linearity: the pattern in the results should not be non-linear (e.g. a U-shape, curvy pattern, etc)
  • Homoskedasticity: “the residuals of your model need to roughly have a similar amount of deviation from your predicted values.”
  1. Collinearity : A VIF factor of 1 indicates no collinearity. Larger VIF factors (>2) are problematic.
  2. Normality of residuals : The histogram should show a normal distribution (bell shape) around 0, and the QQ-plot should show points falling on the diagnonal.
  3. Influential points : Use Influence.ME package
  4. Independence : Mixed model is used to take into account non-independence of values (per subject, per session, etc).
# Adapted VIF function from [here](https://github.com/aufrank/R-hacks/blob/master/mer-utils.R).
vif.mer <- function (fit) {
## adapted from rms::vif
v <- vcov(fit)
nam <- names(fixef(fit))
## exclude intercepts
ns <- sum(1 * (nam == "Intercept" | nam == "(Intercept)"))
if (ns > 0) {
v <- v[-(1:ns), -(1:ns), drop = FALSE]
nam <- nam[-(1:ns)] }
d <- diag(v)^0.5
v <- diag(solve(v/(d %o% d)))
names(v) <- nam 
v }

# Apply function to our model
vif.mer(mdl8)
##         emo3neutral        emo3positive              fbsync 
##            1.070389            1.070029            1.868143 
##        iacc_bingood fbsync:iacc_bingood 
##            1.281595            2.158442

Results

  1. Manipulation check of arousal induction
  1. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence arousal ratings : Within-subject ANOVA (arousal ~ category) OK.
  2. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence valence ratings : Within-subject ANOVA (valence ~ category) OK.
  3. Image category (pos, neg, neutral) will influence HR deceleration : Within-subject ANOVA (hr ~ category) KO.
  1. HR is correlated with arousal ratings : Pearson’s correlation (hr x arousal) KO.
  2. HR is not correlated with valence ratings : Pearson’s correlation (hr x valence) OK
  3. Interoceptive Accuracy (IAcc) is not correlated with arousal ratings : Pearson’s correlation (IAcc x arousal) KO.
  4. Interoceptive Accuracy (IAcc) is not correlated with valence ratings : Pearson’s correlation (IAcc x valence) OK
  1. Cardiac feedback
  1. Feedback effect on arousal ratings (interaction with IAcc) : Mixed MR ANOVA model (arousal ~ category + feedback * IAcc ) OK

  2. No feedback effect on valence ratings : Mixed MR ANOVA model (valence ~ category + feedback * IAcc ) OK Alternative:

  3. Linear Mixed Model (arousal ~ category + feedback * IAcc + (1|id)) OK

  4. Linear Mixed Model (valence ~ category + feedback * IAcc + (1|id)) OK

Interpretation

  • perhaps effect is present but not due to synchronicity (just to feedback itself) : need a baseline (Limit 1)
  • perhaps feedback is not precise enough, or to adjust delays for each person
  • perhaps HR measure is not precise enough (I averaged over a time window ) (since i fail to show different deceleration per emotion, so manipulation not completely effective)
  • IAcc criticized (I acquired control for Depression, Anxiety, but not analysed).

T-test on the differences:

df %>% 
  group_by(iacc_bin, id, emo3) %>%
  mutate(diff = mean(arousal[fb=='async']) - mean(arousal[fb=='sync'],
            n = n())) %>%
  summarise(means = mean(diff)) %>%
  t.test(data = ., means ~ iacc_bin,  alternative = "two.sided", paired = FALSE)
